               <interp inst="t18430227-1097" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18430227"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18430227-1097" type="date" value="18430227"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18430227-1097-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1097-18430227 t18430227-1097-offence-1 t18430227-1097-verdict-1"></join>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184302270247"></xptr>
               <p>1097. <persName id="def1-1097-18430227" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1097-18430227" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1097-18430227" type="age" value="23"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1097-18430227" type="surname" value="WILLIAMSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1097-18430227" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN WILLIAMSON</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18430227-1097-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430227-1097-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430227-1097-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="shoplifting"></interp> for feloniously receiving, of a certain evil-disposed person, on the <rs id="t18430227-cd-237" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430227-1097-offence-1 t18430227-cd-237"></join>23rd of Dec</rs>., 1 bottle, value 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; and 1/2 oz, of oil lavender, 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18430227-name-1454" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1454" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1454" type="surname" value="FULLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1454" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430227-1097-offence-1 t18430227-name-1454"></join>John Fuller</persName>; well knowing them to have been stolen: against the Statute, &amp;c.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1455" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1455" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1455" type="surname" value="FULLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1455" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN FULLER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a chemist and druggist, and live in Crosby-row, Walworth—Weatherhead is in my service—he came the latter end of Oct., or the beginning of Nov.—I received information, and spoke to him on the 13th of Feb.—on the day after he made a communication to me, and in the after<lb></lb>noon I went with the officer, to a place called Camberwell-gate, where we saw the prisoner with a stall, containing cocoa-nuts—I gave him in charge—he asked me what for—I told him my name was Fuller, and he knew my boy better than he knew me—I left him with the officer, and went to his house with the sergeant—I found there this bottle of oil of lavender—I can swear to this bottle as mine, and I had oil of lavender of this description—there was about a shilling's worth of oil of lavender in it—on going to the station I said to the prisoner, "Where have you been in the, habit of getting your essences?"—he said, in the Borough, near a street which I understood was Trinity-street—(he would want them to put into his sweetmeats; they use a great variety of essential oils in sweetmeats)—I asked if it was at Mayne's—he said he didnot know, but he thought it was—I said, "When did you get it there?"—he said in the autumn of the year, mentioning, I think, Oct.—I said, "Where have you got them lately?"—he said Mr. Fuller's boy had brought him some—I said, "That is what I wish to know"—he then said, "I have paid for them."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHARNOCK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Then you said, "That is what I want?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, and I was satisfied when I had obtained what I believed to be the truth—Weatherhead is now in Newgate—I fetched him out to go before the Grand Jury—I have not been to him in Newgate—I wished to see over Newgate, but they would not let me—when I went to the prisoner, he ap<lb></lb>peared to have given up business for the time, on account of the snow or sleet—I have 4000 or 5000 bottles, but not one like this one—the lip of this has been cut off apparently by a diamond—I suppose it is worth 1 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—before I gave Weatherhead into custody I said to him, "I am determined to have justice; if it puts you to inconvenience it is your own fault, but I will give you every recommendation in my power"—I went to get him before the Grand Jury as I thought it would forward justice, as he could explain the matter—this essence that I found at the prisoner's was in a jar in an up-stairs room—it appeared to be a place where he makes his sweetmeats—his wife was in the house, but not in that room.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1456" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1456" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1456" type="surname" value="WEATHERHEAD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1456" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM WEATHERHEAD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am fourteen years old. I was in the employ of Mr. Fuller—I have known the prisoner for the last two years—I had known him before I went to Mr. Fuller—he sells sweetmeats about, and keeps a machine called a dolly—I saw him when I had been about a week at Mr. Fuller's, but he did not say anything to me then—I saw him again a little time afterwards—he then asked me if I saw such things lying about as essence of lemons or cloves, and oil of lavender—I said, "Yes"—he said if I got him such things as he wanted to use in his trade, he would put 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in my way—I did not say anything to that—I know this bottle—I saw it in my master's cupboard—I put into it some oil of lavender, which I found in a small bottle on the shelf—I took it to the prisoner—I do not know on what day—I did not say anything to him, but I gave it him—he did not give me anything then, but on Christmas-day he gave me a sixpence, and on boxing-day</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184302270248"></xptr>
               <p>he gave me another sixpence—that was all the money he ever gave me—I have played at the dolly—I did so about the second Sunday, when he came to the shop, which he kept on Walworth-common—it was before Chirst<lb></lb>mas—when I lost I used to pay him, as I used to have a few halfpence on a Sunday—I did not pay him in any other way—when I won he used to pay me with peppermint, or anything in the shop—my master charged me with robbing him, and then I made a communication to him—the prisoner knew that I took this lavander from my master, because he asked me whether I saw such things about—he did not say anything about paying my master for them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Where have you come from? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> From Newgate—I have been there a little more than a week—I have not been visited by any<lb></lb>body—I once lived next door to the prisoner—he is a housekeeper—he bore a good character—other boys played at this dolly as well as me, and they won sometimes—it is all by chance—when Mr. Fuller said if I would tell him the truth he would do what he could to get me off, I then told him the truth—I do not know that if I get the prisoner convicted that I am to walk home—I have no expectation about that—my master said if I told him the truth he would get me off—I was with Mr. Robinson, a shoemaker, for two years—I left him because I did not like the trade—I live with my mother, in Webb-street—she has not been to see me in Newgate—Mr. Fuller came for me to go before the Grand Jury—the prisoner gave me 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., but he did not tell me to bring him a shilling's worth of this particular stuff—I told him I was at Mr. Fuller's—I know the prisoner uses things of this sort—he did not say, "As you are coming by my stall, bring me so much"—he told me to bring some, and he would pay me—I do not know what this oil of lavander was worth—I do not serve in the shop more than a pennyworth of anything—I did not tell him that this was damaged oil.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was the 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. the prisoner gave you for that laven<lb></lb>der alone? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, for the three articles that I took him, 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. on Christmas-day and 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. on boxing-day—nothing had been said to me about the price I was to have.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1457" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1457" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1457" type="surname" value="ADSHEAD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1457" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM ADSHEAD</persName>
                  </hi>. I live with my father, in Prince's-row, Walworth. I have been in the prisoner's shop before and since Christmas—I remember seeing Weatherhead there one Sunday, about Christmas, and the prisoner passed 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. to him—I have seen Weatherhead play with the dolly there several times.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1458" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1458" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1458" type="surname" value="ADSHEAD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1458" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN ADSHEAD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am Mr. Adshead's brother. I know the prisoner—I have seen Weatherhead at his house three or four times.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1459" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1459" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1459" type="surname" value="BALLARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1459" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE BALLARD</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Portland-street, Walworth. I have seen Weatherhead at the prisoner's house, both before and since Christmas—I have seen him playing at the dolly, and have seen him take parcels there, but I do not know what was in them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1460" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1460" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1460" type="surname" value="DUNN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1460" type="given" value="THOMAS BARNABAS"></interp>THOMAS BARNABAS DUNN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant P</hi> 13.) I saw the prisoner taken into custody at Camberwell-gate.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18430227-1097-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
